Fundamentals of Storage
Introduction
Modern computing systems rely on storage as a foundational component that enables data persistence, retrieval, and processing across a wide range of applications. Unlike volatile memory such as RAM, which temporarily holds data during computation, storage systems are designed to retain information reliably over time, even when power is removed. This fundamental distinction shapes the architecture of operating systems, enterprise applications, and cloud platforms.
Understanding storage involves more than just knowing where data is kept; it requires a clear view of how data is organized, accessed, protected, and scaled across different types of technologies. This document presents a structured and comprehensive introduction to storage fundamentals, guiding the reader through key concepts, technologies, and real-world implementations.
