1. Data Representation in Storage
At its most fundamental level, storage systems manage data in binary form, using sequences of bits represented as zeros and ones. These bits are grouped into bytes, which form the smallest addressable unit of data in most systems. From this basic structure, higher-level abstractions are constructed to organize and interpret data meaningfully.
When data is written to storage, it is encoded according to specific formats such as text, images, or executable instructions. The storage medium itself does not understand the meaning of this data; instead, it simply records electrical, magnetic, or optical signals corresponding to binary values. For example, in magnetic disks, bits are stored by altering the magnetic orientation of small regions on the disk surface, whereas in solid-state drives, bits are stored using electrical charge levels in flash memory cells.
This abstraction enables flexibility, allowing diverse software systems to use the same storage infrastructure while interpreting the stored data differently. The separation between physical storage and logical interpretation is critical for interoperability and scalability across computing environments.
