2. Storage Hierarchy
Storage in computing systems is organized into a hierarchy based on performance, cost, and proximity to the CPU. This hierarchy reflects trade-offs between speed, capacity, and persistence.
At the top of the hierarchy are registers and cache memory, which provide extremely fast access but are limited in size and volatile in nature. Moving down the hierarchy, main memory (RAM) offers larger capacity but still does not retain data after power loss. Persistent storage devices such as solid-state drives (SSDs) and hard disk drives (HDDs) provide long-term data retention but at higher access latency.
This hierarchical design solves the problem of balancing speed and cost. High-speed storage is expensive per unit of capacity, while large-capacity storage is slower but more economical. By combining multiple layers, systems can deliver both performance and scalability. In real-world systems, operating systems actively manage this hierarchy, caching frequently accessed data in faster layers to improve overall performance.
