4. Storage Access Models
Storage systems provide different models for accessing data, each designed to meet specific application requirements.
Block Storage
In block storage, data is stored in fixed-size blocks, each identified by a unique address. Applications interact with block storage through a file system, which organizes these blocks into files and directories. This model provides flexibility and high performance, making it suitable for databases and virtual machines.
The design of block storage allows the operating system to control data placement and access patterns. This abstraction ensures efficiency while maintaining compatibility across different storage devices.
File Storage
File storage presents data as a hierarchical structure of files and directories. Users and applications can access files using paths, simplifying data management. The underlying system handles mapping files to storage blocks.
This approach solves the problem of usability by providing an intuitive interface for storing and retrieving data. Network Attached Storage (NAS) systems commonly use this model in enterprise and collaboration environments.
Object Storage
Object storage organizes data as objects, each containing the data itself, metadata, and a unique identifier. Unlike hierarchical file systems, object storage uses a flat namespace, allowing scalability to billions of objects.
This model is designed for modern cloud applications that require massive scalability, durability, and metadata-rich storage. Services such as backup systems, content delivery networks, and big data platforms rely heavily on object storage.
