5. Storage Architecture
Direct-Attached Storage (DAS)
Direct-attached storage connects storage devices directly to a single host system. This architecture is simple and provides high performance due to minimal overhead. However, it lacks scalability and sharing capabilities, making it suitable primarily for standalone systems.
Network-Attached Storage (NAS)
NAS systems provide file-level access over a network, enabling multiple clients to share storage resources. A NAS device acts as a dedicated file server, managing data access and permissions.
This architecture addresses collaboration needs and simplifies data sharing within organizations. It is commonly used for shared drives, backups, and distributed teams.
Storage Area Network (SAN)
SANs provide block-level access over a dedicated high-speed network. Servers connect to centralized storage arrays, accessing storage as if it were locally attached. This architecture supports high performance and scalability, making it ideal for enterprise workloads such as databases and virtualization platforms.
