6. Data Protection Mechanisms
Ensuring data reliability and availability is a critical aspect of storage systems. Several mechanisms are used to protect data from loss or corruption.
Redundant Array of Independent Disks (RAID) distributes data across multiple disks to improve performance and provide redundancy. Depending on the RAID level, data can be mirrored or striped with parity information, allowing recovery in case of disk failure.
Backups involve creating copies of data and storing them separately, enabling recovery from accidental deletion or system failures. Modern backup solutions often use incremental or differential methods to optimize storage usage.
Replication involves maintaining multiple copies of data across different locations. This ensures high availability and disaster recovery, particularly in distributed systems and cloud environments.
These mechanisms work together to address different failure scenarios, from hardware faults to human errors, ensuring data integrity and business continuity.
