7. Performance Considerations
Storage performance is typically measured in terms of latency, throughput, and input/output operations per second (IOPS). Latency refers to the time taken to complete a single operation, while throughput measures the volume of data transferred over time. IOPS indicates how many read/write operations a system can handle per second.
Performance depends on factors such as the type of storage media, access patterns, and system architecture. For example, SSDs deliver low latency and high IOPS, making them suitable for transactional workloads, while HDDs provide higher throughput for sequential data access.
Caching, tiering, and load balancing are commonly used techniques to optimize performance. These approaches ensure that frequently accessed data resides in faster storage tiers, reducing access time and improving system responsiveness.
