Conclusion
The fundamentals of storage encompass a broad range of concepts, from basic data representation to sophisticated distributed architectures. Each layer of storage technology is designed to address specific challenges, balancing performance, cost, scalability, and reliability.
By understanding how storage systems work, why they are structured in particular ways, and where they are applied, engineers and users can make informed decisions that align with application requirements and organizational goals. This knowledge forms the foundation for exploring advanced topics such as cloud storage, storage virtualization, and data lifecycle management.

